\section*{EXAMPLE 2.12}

Solve: $\frac{4 q+3}{2}+6=\frac{3 q+5}{4}$
(J) Solution
$$\frac{4 q+3}{2}+6=\frac{3 q+5}{4}$$

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Multiply both sides by the LCD, 4. & $4\left(\frac{4 q+3}{2}+6\right)=4\left(\frac{3 q+5}{4}\right)$ \\
\hline Distribute. & $4\left(\cdot \frac{4 q+3}{2}\right)+4 \cdot 6=4 \cdot\left(\frac{3 q+5}{4}\right)$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $2(4 q+3)+24=3 q+5$ \\
\hline & $8 q+6+24=3 q+5$ \\
\hline & $8 q+30=3 q+5$ \\
\hline Collect the variables to the left. & $8 q-3 q+30=3 q-3 q+5$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $5 q+30=5$ \\
\hline Collect the constants to the right. & $5 q+30-30=5-30$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $5 q=-25$ \\
\hline Divide both sides by five. & $\frac{5 q}{5}=\frac{-25}{5}$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $q=-5$ \\
\hline Check: $\quad \frac{4 q+3}{2}+6=\frac{3 q+5}{4}$ & \\
\hline Let $q=-5 . \quad \frac{4(-5)+3}{2}+6 \stackrel{?}{=} \frac{3(-5)+5}{4}$ & \\
\hline Finish the check on your own. & \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
