\end{tabular}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\begin{tabular}{c}
Time \\
(hrs)
\end{tabular}$=$\begin{tabular}{c}
Distance \\
(miles)
\end{tabular}} \\
\hline Walk & $r$ & $\frac{1}{2}$ & $\frac{1}{2} r$ \\
\hline Bike & $r+3$ & $\frac{1}{4}$ & $\frac{1}{4}(r+3)$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

The equation will come from the fact that the distance from Naoko's home to her school is the same whether she is walking or riding her bike.
So we say:
$$\text { distance walked }=\text { distance covered by bike }$$

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Translate to an equation. & $\frac{1}{2} r \quad=\quad \frac{1}{4}(r+3)$ \\
\hline Solve this equation. & $\frac{1}{2} r=\frac{1}{4}(r+3)$ \\
\hline Clear the fractions by multiplying by the LCD of all the fractions in the equation. & $8 \cdot \frac{1}{2} r=8 \cdot \frac{1}{4}(r+3)$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

Simplify.
$$\begin{aligned}
4 r & =2(r+3) \\
4 r & =2 r+6 \\
2 r & =6 \\
r & =3 \mathrm{mph} \quad \text { walking speed } \\
r & +3 \quad \text { biking speed } \\
3 & +3
\end{aligned}$$

6

Let's check if this works.
Walk $3 \mathrm{mph}(0.5$ hour $) \quad=1.5$ miles
Bike $6 \mathrm{mph}(0.25$ hour $)=1.5$ miles

Yes, either way Naoko travels 1.5 miles to school.
Naoko's walking speed is 3 mph and her speed riding her bike is 6 mph .

