When solving inequalities, it is usually easiest to collect the variables on the side where the coefficient of the variable is largest. This eliminates negative coefficients and so we don't have to multiply or divide by a negative-which means we don't have to remember to reverse the inequality sign.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.53}

Solve the inequality $8 p+3(p-12)>7 p-28$, graph the solution on the number line, and write the solution in interval notation.

\section*{Solution}
$$8 p+3(p-12)>7 p-28$$

Simplify each side as much as possible.

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Distribute. & $8 p+3 p-36>7 p-28$ \\
\hline Combine like terms. & $11 p-36>7 p-28$ \\
\hline Subtract $7 p$ from both sides to collect the variables on the left, since $11>7$. & $11 p-36-7 p>7 p-28-7 p$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $4 p-36>-28$ \\
\hline Add 36 to both sides to collect the constants on the right. & $4 p-36+36>-28+36$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $4 p>8$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
\hline Divide both sides of the inequality by 4; the inequality stays the same. & $\frac{4 p}{4}>\frac{8}{4}$ & \\
\hline Simplify. & $p>2$ & \\
\hline Graph the solution on the number line. & ![](./images/fc686fde-1413-455c-8a02-0a26b98e7fc3-0187_75_420_456_866.jpg) & \\
\hline Write the solution in interval notation. & ( $2, \infty$ ) & \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

