To solve an absolute value equation, we first isolate the absolute value expression using the same procedures we used to solve linear equations. Once we isolate the absolute value expression we rewrite it as the two equivalent equations.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.69}

\section*{How to Solve Absolute Value Equations}

Solve $|5 x-4|-3=8$.

\section*{Solution}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
\hline Step 1. Isolate the absolute value expression. & Add 3 to both sides. & $$\begin{aligned}
|5 x-4|-3 & =8 \\
|5 x-4| & =11
\end{aligned}$$ \\
\hline Step 2. Write the equivalent equations. & & $5 x-4=-11$ or $5 x-4=11$ \\
\hline Step 3. Solve each equation. & \begin{tabular}{l}
Add 4 to each side. \\
Divide each side by 5 .
\end{tabular} & $$\begin{array}{rlrlrl}
5 x & =-7 & & 5 x & =15 \\
x & =-\frac{7}{5} & \text { or } & & x & =3
\end{array}$$ \\
\hline Step 4. Check each solution. & Substitute 3 and $-\frac{7}{5}$ into the original equation. & $$\begin{aligned}
