Some of our absolute value equations could be of the form $|u|=|v|$ where $u$ and $v$ are algebraic expressions. For example, $|x-3|=|2 x+1|$.

How would we solve them? If two algebraic expressions are equal in absolute value, then they are either equal to each
other or negatives of each other. The property for absolute value equations says that for any algebraic expression, $u$, and a positive real number, $a$, if $|u|=a$, then $u=-a$ or $u=a$.

This tells us that
$$\begin{array}{ll}
\text { if } & |u|=|v| \\
\text { then } & u=-v
\end{array} \text { or } u=v$$

This leads us to the following property for equations with two absolute values.

\section*{Equations with Two Absolute Values}

For any algebraic expressions, $u$ and $v$,
$$\begin{array}{ll}
\text { if } & |u|=|v| \\
\text { then } & u=-v \text { or } u=v
\end{array}$$

When we take the opposite of a quantity, we must be careful with the signs and to add parentheses where needed.

\section*{EXAMPLE 2.72}

Solve: $|5 x-1|=|2 x+3|$.

\section*{Solution}
$$|5 x-1|=|2 x+3|$$

Write the equivalent equations.
$$\begin{array}{rlrlrl}
5 x-1 & =-(2 x+3) & \text { or } & & 5 x-1 & =2 x+3 \\
5 x-1 & =-2 x-3 & & \text { or } & & 3 x-1 \\
7 x-1 & =-3 & & 3 x & =4 \\
7 x & =-2 & & x & =\frac{4}{3} \\
x & =-\frac{2}{7} & & \text { or } & x & =\frac{4}{3}
\end{array}$$

Check.

We leave the check to you.
